'''Glass onions''' were large [[glass blowing|hand blown]] [[glass]] [[bottle|bottles]] used aboard [[sailing ship|sailing ships]] to hold [[wine]] or [[brandy]]. 
For increased stability on rough seas, the bottles were fashioned with a wide-bottom shape to prevent toppling, thus making the bottles look somewhat [[onion]]-shaped.

'''''Glass Onion''''' is also the name of a song by [[The Beatles]], written by John Lennon and Paul McCartney, featured on the [[White Album]]. It is notable for it containing references to four other Beatles songs; [[Strawberry Fields]], [[I Am the Walrus]], [[Lady Madonna]] and [[The Fool on the Hill]]. Some people also claim it contains a clue to the [[Paul is Dead]] conspiracy with the line "The walrus was Paul", because the walrus is an animal that is linked with death in certain cultures.


